org.nineml.coffeegrinder.parser

Interface TreeWalker

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    DefaultTreeWalker

    public interface TreeWalker
    The TreeWalker works with a TreeBuilder to construct parse trees from the graph.

    How the class that implements this interface gets the builder (or even, technically), if it does, is implementation defined.

    Users can treat this as a kind of iterator, usign hasNext(), next(), and walk() to construct trees from the graph.

    • Method Detail

      • getTotalParses

        long getTotalParses()
        Returns the total number of parses available.

        If the total number is larger than Long.MAX_VALUE, MAX_VALUE should be returned. The getExactTotalParses() method will return the correct value.

        Returns:
        the total number of parses

      • getExactTotalParses

        java.math.BigInteger getExactTotalParses()
        Returns the exact total number of parses avialable.

        In an ambigous parse, there may be many (many!) possible trees. This method returns the exact number, even if it's larger than will fit in a long.

        Returns:
        the exact total number of parses

      • getRemainingParses

        long getRemainingParses()
        Returns the number of parses remaining.

        If an ambiguous parse has multiple trees, the walker may allow you to iterate through them. If so, this method should return the number remaining. If the number is larger than Long.MAX_VALUE, MAX_VALUE should be returned. The getExactRemainingParses() method will return the correct value.

        Returns:
        the remaining number of parses

      • getExactRemainingParses

        java.math.BigInteger getExactRemainingParses()
        Returns the exact number of parses remaining.

        If an ambiguous parse has multiple trees, the walker may allow you to iterate through them. If so, this method should return the number remaining.

        Returns:
        the remaining number of parses

      • walk

        void walk()
        Walk the graph, producing the current tree.

        The walker will make calls into the TreeBuilder to construct the tree.

        If walk is called more than once, it should return the same tree each time. To advance to the next tree, call next().

      • hasNext

        boolean hasNext()
        Are there any more parses?
        Returns:
        true if there are more parses available

      • next

        void next()
        Advance to the next parse.

      • reset

        void reset()
        Reset parsing.

        If this method is called, the walker should reset to its initial state and begin returning the same sequence of trees that it did when it was first created.

      • getTreeBuilder

        TreeBuilder getTreeBuilder()

        Returns:
